{{日本の位階}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:しようろくい}}
[[Category:位階制度|しよう6い]]

{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}
'''Shōrokui''' (正六位) is one of the {{ill|Ranks of Japan|ja|位階|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shinkai (divine rank)|lt=divine ranks|ja|神階|1=Shinkai (divine rank)|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is positioned below {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|ja|従五位|1=Junior Fifth Rank|12=draft|12=draft}} and above {{ill|Junior Sixth Rank|ja|従六位|1=Junior Sixth Rank|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>https://www.wakapoetry.net/background/society/court-offices-titles-and-ranks/court-ranks/</ref> In terms of decorations, it corresponds to the Fifth Class of {{ill|Orders of Merit|ja|勲等|12=draft|12=draft}} and the Fifth Class of the {{ill|Order of the Golden Kite|ja|金鵄勲章|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Sixth Rank was granted to {{ill|Kaike|ja|介|12=draft|12=draft}}, who served as the deputy governor of lower provinces. It was classified as a rank for {{ill|Jige|ja|地下人|12=draft|12=draft}} (non-court nobles) and was distinctly separate from the Fifth Rank or higher, which denoted nobility ({{ill|Tsūki|ja|通貴|12=draft|12=draft}}). Those holding the Sixth Rank were not permitted {{ill|Shōden|ja|昇殿|12=draft|12=draft}} (entry to the palace). However, {{ill|Kurōdo|ja|蔵人|12=draft|12=draft}} (Chamberlains) were exceptions; their roles allowed them palace access, and those of the Sixth Rank were called {{ill|Rokui Kurōdo|ja|六位蔵人|12=draft|12=draft}}, collectively referred to as {{ill|Tenjōbito|ja|殿上人|12=draft|12=draft}} alongside those of the Fifth Rank or higher.
In terms of {{ill|Shinkai (divine rank)|lt=divine ranks|ja|神階|1=Shinkai (divine rank)|12=draft|12=draft}}, Shōrokui is the lowest rank. The {{ill|Samurai|ja|侍|12=draft|12=draft}} originated from the {{ill|Samuraihon|ja|侍品|12=draft|12=draft}} class, which consisted of individuals limited to the Sixth Rank who served as bureaucrats and aides to nobles. The Sixth Rank class was also referred to as {{ill|Aosamurai|ja|青侍|12=draft|12=draft}} (Blue Samurai) due to their {{ill|Po (clothing)|lt=Po robe|ja|袍|ja|袍|12=draft|12=draft}} being light blue in color.
In the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft}} and later, individuals holding ranks such as {{ill|Major|ja|少佐|12=draft|12=draft}} were appointed to this position.
Today, Shōrokui is posthumously conferred to individuals such as {{ill|Keishisei|ja|警視正|12=draft|12=draft}} (Senior Police Superintendent) in the {{ill|Japanese police|ja|日本の警察官|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shōbōkan|ja|消防監|12=draft|12=draft}} (Fire Superintendent) in the {{ill|Firefighting personnel|ja|消防吏員|12=draft|12=draft}}, chairs of {{ill|Municipal councils in Japan|ja|日本の地方議会|12=draft|12=draft}} (city, town, and village councils), founders of special institutions and schools, and artists who have made significant contributions in their respective fields.
